<font color="#FF0000">PTSD</font><br>
<tt>Fri Oct  3  6:26:12 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I haven't made any entries in this thread simply because I don't feel as if I suffer from PTSD.<br><br>
Recently I have begun to look back at the way I was for a few years after I returned from Vietnam. It has occurred to me that possibly I had the symptoms of the disorder, but was able to keep them under control.<br><br>
One thing that I did was pack up my stuff and move to the hills of Tennessee. I was a 23 year old Vietnam veteran who wanted nothing from nobody. Still feel pretty much the same as I continue to be self employed. I consider myself successful and one of the very fortunate ones. Always will.<br><br>
I found God many years after I returned and have always felt myself to be a spiritual person. This has helped me, I feel.<br><br>
I believe it was Cook Barela who surmised that some cases of PTSD were possibly brought about in guys who were mistreated when they returned home. I have heard others say this. Is it possible to draw a difference between this and  combat experience? If so, then it appears that it would be harder to treat psychological wounds caused by combat than it would be to treat or &quot;unlearn&quot; a feeling of rejection. <br>
Could the feeling of rejection (and anger or hopelessness) be a result of the way we look at *ourselves*? Our attitudes? <br><br>
There has never been a time that I was ashamed of having served in VN. So it was not likely any outside influence could make me feel badly.<br><br>
Moving to Tennessee and leaving Chicago and the security of my family for the unknown was a major step for a 23 year old. The ONLY ONLY reason that I was able to do something so bold was *because of my Vietnam experience*. Nothing could be so difficult as that!<br><br>
As I said, I have no idea of what PTSD is, but Vietnam is always in the back of my mind - enabling me to take on all challenges.<br><br>
For me it is a matter of BEING and having been there.<br><br>
Peace.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman#greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


